{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492257"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.68,0.19,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89870"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1024"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74039"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"129"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89870"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a few hours\u0027 history of severe pain behind his left eye and double vision. He has no significant medical history except for type 2 diabetes mellitus, which is poorly controlled due to medication non-compliance. His regular medications include metformin. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks wine every other evening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His vital signs are within normal limits. His left eye is fixed in the outward position with restricted movement in all directions except lateral gaze. Both pupils are reactive to light. The right eye examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facial nerve palsy","Trigeminal neuralgia","Oculomotor nerve palsy","Abducens nerve palsy","Trochlear nerve palsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute onset of pain behind the eye, diplopia, and restricted eye movement with the eye fixed in an outward position. These findings are classic for an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E. The oculomotor (third cranial) nerve innervates most of the extraocular muscles (superior, inferior and medial recti, inferior oblique), the levator palpebrae superioris (which elevates the eyelid), and carries parasympathetic fibres to the pupil. When this nerve is affected, the eye typically assumes a \u0027down and out\u0027 position due to the unopposed action of the lateral rectus (CN VI) and superior oblique (CN IV) muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient has a pupil-sparing oculomotor nerve palsy, which is commonly caused by microvascular ischaemia in patients with diabetes. The poorly controlled diabetes makes this the most likely aetiology. However, the presence of pain is concerning and raises the possibility of a posterior communicating artery aneurysm compressing the nerve. This is a neurological emergency requiring urgent neuroimaging, as rupture of such aneurysms carries a high mortality rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrochlear nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E (fourth cranial nerve) affects the superior oblique muscle, resulting in vertical diplopia that worsens with downward gaze and head tilt toward the affected side. Patients typically present with compensatory head tilt away from the affected side. The eye would not be fixed in the outward position as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbducens nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E (sixth cranial nerve) affects the lateral rectus muscle, causing horizontal diplopia that worsens with gaze toward the affected side. The affected eye would be unable to abduct (move outward), which is inconsistent with this patient\u0027s presentation where lateral gaze is preserved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacial nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E (seventh cranial nerve) causes weakness of facial muscles on the affected side, including inability to close the eye, flatten the nasolabial fold, or elevate the corner of the mouth. It does not cause diplopia or affect eye movements, making it inconsistent with this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal neuralgia\u003C/strong\u003E (fifth cranial nerve) presents as paroxysmal, severe, electric shock-like pain in the distribution of one or more branches of the trigeminal nerve. It is not associated with diplopia or abnormal eye movements, making it an unlikely diagnosis for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oculomotor nerve palsy presents with diplopia, restricted eye movement in all directions except lateral gaze, and the eye fixed in a down and out position.","Pupil-sparing oculomotor nerve palsy is commonly caused by microvascular ischaemia in patients with diabetes or hypertension.","Painful oculomotor nerve palsy requires urgent neuroimaging to exclude a posterior communicating artery aneurysm."],"references":["Margolin E, Freund P. Third Nerve Palsies: Review. Int Ophthalmol Clin. 2019 Summer. 59 (3):99-112. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31233418/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74039"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19121"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19121"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bf7a780d-54f0-40cf-9e4d-fd4e5d85454d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bf7a780d-54f0-40cf-9e4d-fd4e5d85454d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":579,"height":385}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74039"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T13:21:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T13:24:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1024"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89870"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":